    </section>


    <section id="id11417048">
      <title>Mixed halides</title>

      <para id="id15502990">Mixed halides are an important class of halocarbon compound. They are synthesized by halide exchange, <link target-id="eip-5553"/>. The high cost of SbF<sub>3</sub> means that the reaction is generally run with an excess of the chloride. </para>





<equation id="eip-5553">
<media id="id245922_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/Eq36.jpg" id="id245922__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media>
</equation>








      <para id="id16006012">The ordinary name for mixed carbon halide is halon or Freon, although Freon is actually a Du Pont trademark. A list of selected Freon compounds are given in <link target-id="id15659072"/>. Halons are non-toxic, non-flammable, and have no odor. However, it is their very lack of reactivity that has caused a problem. </para>


